    Naruto... Either you love him or you hate him, there is no denying the fact that the manga and anime are huge successes. Being one of the big 3 alongside Bleach and One Piece, Naruto is considered to be the most popular anime in the UK, US, and Canada, so it is definitely a money maker for Studio Pierrot and Shonen Jump, and you can definitely see that in how the anime was handled. Before I start this review, I want you to know that I am actually a HUGE fan of this franchise. In fact, the manga and anime is the reason why I\
          \
        started watching other shows. This anime also has affected me in a personal level, so this will without a doubt affect my overall score of the show. As you can probably see, I gave this show a 10, but that's due to my love for the show. HOWEVER, the final score I will be giving this anime in the review will be solely based on the show, and I will try my best to be unbiased.\
Story - 6\
Everybody knows the basic premise of this show. A young ninja who is ostracised by everyone due to the fact that he is the Jinchuuriki of the Kyubi (Nine Tailed Fox) that destroyed the Hidden Leaf Village. The truth is I love the story of the original manga. While many consider the story to be generic shonen that doesn't try anything to differentiate itself, those who say that usually don't realise that Naruto is one of the reasons why there are so many shonens following the same formula. The story worked, it's easy to follow, and it's really inspiring, and the success of that formula has led to many shonen stories after it to follow the same structure. HOWEVER, this is hardly present in the anime. This is due to the incredible amount of filler that just brings the story down. The flow of the story is continuously interrupted due to stupid filler episodes. There were only a handful of filler that I found enjoyable. An example would be the episode where Team 7 tries to figure out what's under Kakashi's mask. While I can definitely endure filler episodes if I love the franchise enough, and that is definitely true for Naruto because I was able to watch every single episode, and rewatch it again years later, I still think that the story could have been better if these fillers at least had a little substance. \
Art - 6\
I think you've probably seen the pictures of characters in the anime having outstretched limbs and weird facial expressions. A very popular one is Sasuke looking weird as hell in his battle against Naruto in the Final Valley. However, this is a common animation technique that even the very successful video game OVERWATCH uses in the game, so I won't criticise Studio Pierrot for doing it. In fact, the fight scenes are probably the best parts of every episode, due to the animation. But sadly, this anime isn't as beautiful as it should have been. If you read the original manga, you would definitely agree with me when I say that Masashi Kishimoto is probably a master in adding attention to detail. His pages are gorgeous, and sadly the anime cannot replicate it. To be honest, Studio Pierrot is definitely capable of creating a beautifully looking anime, but sadly it seems like they got lazy when animating this series.\
Sound - 8\
Naruto's soundtrack beautifully merges traditional japanese instruments with Rock, creating an interesting fusion that works well with the series. In fact, no anime's soundtrack is as iconic as Naruto's. The main theme is easily recognisable for any anime fan, and there is a reason for that. The openings are also fantastic. Perfect examples are GO!!! and Re:member by the band FLOW, and Haruka Kanata by the extremely talented Asian Kung Fu Generation. As a non-japanese speaker, I still find these songs to be awesome. Especially when I was a kid, I would listen to these songs almost everyday on my way to school (pretty embarrassing now that I think about it).\
Character - 7\
I can't hate the characters for one reason, the anime does an AMAZING job in developing the cast. Because the series is long-running, the anime can dedicate episodes to many of its characters, so at no point does any of the characters seem useless to the story. Naruto is your typical shonen MC. Stupid, loud mouthed, huge appetite, and the willingness to never give up. Again, I believe that Naruto is one of the reasons alongside Goku and Luffy that this archetype is so common in many animes, so I don't think I should criticise Naruto for being generic.\
Enjoyment - 10\
I think this section of the review is based on my PERSONAL experience, so I obviously will give it a 10. This anime has a special place in my heart, and has affected me greatly. I love this series so much to the point that I overlook many of its flaws. I know a TRUE fan would be enraged at how Studio Pierrot handled the anime, but to me, I just love this series for starting my love of anime and manga.\
Overall - 6\
I gave it a 10 because of what Naruto has done for me. However, this final score is based solely on my review, and it definitely isn't a masterpiece. I still believe that this anime is a trendsetter, and for better or worse is one of the reasons for the incredible amount of shonen manga and anime in the late 90s and early 2000s. That's why I think it's an OKAY anime, but it's flaws keep it from being a great anime. Sadly, if handled by a different studio, this anime could have been just as good as One Piece and DBZ, but the limitations of budget, and Studio Pierrot's dedication to profit rather than creating an amazing series has led them to creating this series. However, I love it for what it is.\
