        that evolves a lot trough the run of the show and are given a lot of character, but they are far from the only ones. However, there are many people that dislike this group of protagonists and I can get why. Sakura grows a lot, but the way she starts off, and even some of the traits she keeps until the very end of Naruto, are quite the annoyance. She sees herself as superior to Naruto at the beginning even if she's shown repeatedly that she can't do much to help her partners, is very off putting. Nevertheless, Sakura realizes this and makes a good effort to better herself for the sake of the team and her own, and that ties directly with the themes of the show of giving it your all to achieve a goal. Then, a Character I personally dislike is Sasuke Uchiha, Naruto's rival. The fact that his character plays such a massive role on this show makes his problems all the more apparent. However, it's much more bearable in Naruto than he is in Shippuden. He works well as to motivate Naruto to be better, beating Sasuke is another goal to reach, and Sasuke sees Naruto as a rival as well, something I appreciate. Now, the problem to me comes when at the end of the show, Sasuke's actions throw all his development out the window as it had never happened, and this very off-putting action is the driving force behind Shippuden. I must say that he does have some reasons to do this, but I don't think they're nearly enough to justify them. Moving to Naruto himself, I think he's a very strong protagonist and works amazingly, his backstory and determination makes the audience want to cheer for him, besides being a very funny character. He acts like the kid he is, in fact, they all do, which is a good bit of characterization since these characters are only 12 years old. \
Now, the supporting cast is by far the strongest I've ever seen. All of them have their own lovable and unique personalities, and are just as awesome, if not more, as the main cast. However, I have to address the problem of most female characters in this show; they're not given as much characterization as the others, with a few exceptions such as Hinata Hyuga.\
In what regards the villains, they are just great. Haku and Zabuza are personal favourites, just as the big bad guy of the show. They're all interesting and have believable motivations, aside from being capable of putting up great battles for the audience's enjoyment.\
Personally, I find the battles in Naruto are much more interesting in this show than the ones found in the sequel. This is due to the fact that these ninjas are still in training, so they have to use the few abilities they know creatively as to achieve victory. These battles are all really exciting, even if they drag a bit from time to time.\
Now, let's address the elephant in the room, the filler arcs. It's not as atrocious in Naruto as it will get in Shippuden, but there is a lot of filler, and it's mostly bad, with an exception being the episode where they try to see under Kakashi's mask. Luckily, skipping it is always an option.\
Then, there's the animation quality. This show is rather old, and its animation quality was never the best. I never gave much importance to those aspects of a show, but I know it can be off-putting for some people.\
A major point in favour of this show is its OST. If you go and listen to some, you'll notice their unique style given to them by the traditional instruments, and the amount of perfectly conveyed emotions each of these carries.\
Another point I'd like to address, is the sheer amount of emotions this show will make you feel. It's mostly a happy-go-lucky show, but it's more than capable of making you cry. In addition, it's far from a \"dumb\" show. One of its villains acts out of wanting to have a purpose for living pretty early in the show, and I loved it.\
Finally yet importantly, Naruto's story shows to be more than just his journey to becoming Hokage. It's a story that involves more than our protagonist, but the whole world they live in. It is not fully developed in Naruto as it is in Shippuden, but I must say the amount of things going on in Shippuden is overbearing, and Naruto is much easier to follow, and just as interesting.\
\
To sum up, I think it's worth watching as long as you can put up with its length. Its strongest point to me, being the characters, even if, in my opinion, it a few things wrong with these, it doesn't nullify the rest. Therefore, in addition to good action scenes, a great deal of emotions, comedy, and an easy to follow story, I hold this show very dear to my heart, even if the amount of filler and animation doesn't really help it.",
